In the Mediterranean, the scientific knowledge about seamounts contains large gaps, mainly on the eastern basin, but also by an asymmetry between the amount of geological and biological studies (

). Recent surveys carried out in the Mallorca Channel seamounts, including Ausias March, Ses Olives and Emile Baudot seamounts (

), have substantially improved our knowledge of Mediterranean invertebrates. This improvement has been particularly important for sponges, with the description, so far, of seven new species (

; 

), but also echinoderms, with the report of the first Mediterranean record of a brittle star of the family 
Ophiohelidae Perrier, 1873
, 

Ophiomyces grandis
Lyman, 1879

, which showed high abundances in these seamounts despite its absence from insular coasts (

).
